[1] Haiti update
Date: Mon 22 Nov 2010
Source: Haiti Libre [edited]
<http://www.haitilibre.com/en/news-1715-haiti-epidemic-last-assessment-23377-cases-1344-deaths-the-cholera-gains-the-south.html>


The epidemic in Haiti could easily get worse despite efforts to control it,
say the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and [Pan
American] Health Organization (PAHO).

Dr Scott Dowell, infectious disease specialist, said "with regard to the
eradication of cholera in Haiti, we have little hope at this point, we
believe that Haiti will have to treat cholera for several years." Recalling
that "the treatment is simple, fast, and can save many lives and it is on
this aspect that health authorities focus."

The NGO Terre des Hommes (TDH) is stepping up briefings and prevention of
cholera in the departments, West and South of Haiti, where the Swiss
organization Save the Children supports some 50 000 earthquake victims.

Professor Michel Roulet, of TDH, which has conducted numerous missions in
Haiti, warns "I have personally witnessed 4 outbreaks of cholera in various
parts of the world but I never saw the spread stopped, whatever the
hardness of the measures taken. We must prepare ourselves to deal with long
weeks of illness until the peak of the epidemic. Then it will take weeks
before it is reduced, knowing there will be new outbreaks in subsequent years."

The latest assessment (cumulative) dated Fri 19 Nov 2010 and published
today [22 Nov 2010] by the Ministry of Public Health and Population (MSPP)
reported 23 377 hospitalizations since the beginning of the epidemic, 2510
additional cases since the last official assessment of 17 Nov 2010 (+12.02
per cent) and 1344 deaths, 94 new additional deaths (+7.52 per cent).

In Port-au-Prince and metropolitan area, (Port-au-Prince: Carrefour, Cite
Soleil, Delmas, Kenscoff, Petion-Ville, Port-au-Prince, Tabarre, and Croix
des Bouquets) 1618 hospitalizations have been reported since the 1st
reported case in this area, that is, 161 additional cases since the last
assessment (187 Nov 2010) (+11.05 per cent) and 77 deaths, 13 new
additional deaths (+20,31 per cent).

The victims in isolated communities are little or not reported. Mortality
rates in the north east (14 per cent), south (9.5 per cent) and south east
(18.2 per cent) were the highest in the country (mortality including deaths
in hospital and community)

