[3] Dominican Republic: update
Date: Thu 18 Nov 2010
Source: Listin Diario [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
<http://www.listindiario.com.do/la-republica/2010/11/18/167056/>


Several suspected cases of cholera are currently under investigation in the
country, including a 3 year old child and a woman who have been admitted to
the San Lorenzo de Los Mina hospital, and a 30 year old Haitian who has
been admitted in a hospital in the El Almirante sector after arriving in
the country from Chile, via Panama.

The public health minister, Bautista Rojas Gomez, said that between 13 and
14 different cultures of patients with suspicious signs are currently under
investigation in the National Laboratory.

The child tested positive by a rapid test, but is awaiting lab results. The
Haitian man with suspected cholera arrived from Chile via Panama, with
symptoms of the disease. He was detected by the system upon arrival at the
airport and admitted in the care center at El Almirante, in North Santo
Domingo, where he is isolated. The hospital director, Aracelis Cruz Jaquez,
said that the patient was transferred to the center at 2:30 in the morning
and at noon yesterday [16 Nov 2010] he was stable and hydrated.

She explained that the patient has been living for 2 years in the country,
had visited Haiti in October 2010, and then traveled to Chile where he has
relatives, but there fell ill and was returned to the country via Panama.
He was met by a committee of public health epidemiologists, who took him to
the clinic.

The Ministry of Public Health is conducting active surveillance for
diarrhea in the whole country, with visits to each house. When a case is
found it will be recorded in the system and closely monitored.

[byline: Doris Pantaleon]

--
communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
